\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Fiat currencies:}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 For fiat currencies I use the ISO 4217 currency code in front of the currency symbol. ISO 4217 ties the currency name to the country code to remove ambiguity and is recommended for currency names that are shared across many countries such as the dollar, pound, crown, lira, won and rupee.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Here is a concise table of the most common currencies and their respective ISO 4217 code:}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 USD, EUR, GBP, INR, KOW, JPY, RUB, CZK}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Some countries have unique currency names with accompanying symbols such as the Euro (\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8364\'80), Israeli new shekel (\u8362\'3F), Japanese yen (\u165\'A5), Russian ruble (\u8381\'3F) and Thai Baht (\u3647\'3F).}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Support for certain currency symbols is not guaranteed among fonts, in those situations just use the ISO 4217 code on its own.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Some currencies also don\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92t have an official currency symbol.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Cryptocurrencies:}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 I refer to cryptocurrencies in full and with their suggested currency symbol (and pseudo-ISO 4217 code if applicable). Bitcoin (\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8383\'3F) is the only cryptocurrency with a recognised currency symbol within Unicode which supersedes the Thai Baht symbol unless the chosen font doesn\u8217\'92t support it.}
